<b><font size="+2"><center>Relations</center></b>
<b><font size="+1"><center>Learning Plan 1</center></b>
<P>
<b><center>Introduction</center></b><font size="--">
<P>Relations consider a certain connection between pairs of objects taken in a definite order   (ordered pairs).</P>

<P>(a,b) = (c,d)  IFF a = c and b = d &#9;&#9;(IFF = if and only if)</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Product Sets</P>
</B>
<P>Have two sets A and B.   The set of all ordered pairs (a,b) where a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 A and b <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 B is called the product of A and B (write A <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 B).</P>

<P>A <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 B = {(a,b) : a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 A, b <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 B}</P>

<B><P>Example </P>
</B>
<P>A = {1,2}, B = {a, b, c}</P>

<P>A <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 B = {(1,a), (1,b), (1,c), (2,a), (2,b), (2,c)}</P>

<P>B <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 A = {(a,1), (b,1), (c,1), (a,2), (b,2), (c,2)}</P>

<B><P>Relations</P>
</B>
<P>Let A and B be sets.   A relation from A to B is a subset of A <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 B.</P>

<P>If R is a relation from A to B,  for each pair a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 A and b <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 B, one of the following is true:-</P>

<P>- (a,b) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R, ‘a is related to b’, write a R b</P>

<P>- (a,b) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#207;</FONT>
 R,  ‘a is not related to b'</P>
<B>
<P>Domain</B> of the relation R is the set of all first elements of the ordered pairs.</P>

<B><P>Range</B> of the relation R is the set of all second elements of the ordered pairs.</P>
<P>
<B><P>Example </P>
</B>
<P>A = {1, 2, 3}, B = {x, y, z}</P>
<P>Let R = {(1,y), (1,z), (3,y)}</P>

<P>R is a relation from A to B as R is a subset of A <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 B</P>

<P>Here&#9;1 R y,&#9;&#9;1 R z,&#9;&#9;3 R y</P>

<P>Domain of R is {1,3}</P>
<P>Range of R is {y,z}</P>
<P>
<B><P>Equality</B> is an important relationship on a set A. {(a ,a) : a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 A}</P>

<br>
<B><P>Universal Relation</B> for a set A. </P>

<P>A <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 A is a subset of A <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 A.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Empty Relation</B> on a set A</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#198;</FONT>
 is a subset of A <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#180;</FONT>
 A.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Inverse Relation</P>
</B>
<P>If R is a relation from A to B,  then the inverse , R<SUP>-1 </SUP>is a relation from B to A.</P>

<P>R<SUP>-1 </SUP>= {(b ,a)  :  (a, b) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
R}</P>

<B><P>Example</P>
</B>
<P>Inverse of the relation R = {(1, y), (1, z), (3, y)} from A = {1, 2, 3},  B = {x, y, z} is </P>

<P>R<SUP>-1 </SUP>= {(y, 1), (z, 1), (y, 3)}.</P></BODY>
